pageSummary: Raising money for Macmillan Cancer Support because this was the charity Linda supported in her life.
pageSummaryWhat: Raising money for Macmillan Cancer Support
pageSummaryWhy: this was the charity Linda supported in her life.
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Linda Walker
story:
Linda was taken from us all far too early. She passed after a short but brave battle with cancer.

Linda was a real force and everyone that met her loved her. She leaves behind so many friends that would wish to help celebrate her life, and she was clear that rather than have flowers that she would like something constructive would come of it and wanted to raise funds for Macmillan Cancer Support. 

Please give what you are able to in her memory, I know that Linda would have appreciated it, as well as her daughter Victoria and partner David.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Cancer is something we all hope we never have to deal with
in our lives, but one in two of us will be directly affected by this terrible
disease.

MCRactive is taking a stand to fund life-saving research and care for those impacted by Cancer, by supporting Macmillan.

For many of us, this cause is close to hearts, and Macmillan has provided invaluable help, advice and nursing to loved ones. So, for 2020, we’re aiming to raise £500 to help fight cancer.

We hope you can support and join us on our Coffee Morning. Cheers!

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
It’s that time of year again!

The Letters from Postal Santa Service has returned to help raise donations for Macmillan Cancer Support.

2020 has made it hard to celebrate Christmas how we usually would, and The Letters from Santa Postal Service want to make it as festive and magical for you and your family as we can.

You can get hand-written letters from Santa to make a child’s Christmas genuinely magical, stress-free, and help you bring back the true spirit of Christmas by fuelling children’s imagination and a healthy sense of fantasy and delight.

Charities are struggling now more than ever during these difficult times. With just a minimum donation of £5 per letter, you can help support Macmillan and all their fantastic work.

To request a letter, please fill out the form below. 

https://forms.office.com/Pages/ResponsePage.aspx?id=fEsfdpUAckyqjnCEs7uopuXNz8EVpORNnGf7trjQEPtUN1E1TURaV1o3N0w5MEdSUzNQVDU3WUVBMC4u

Many thanks to all of you who have bought a letter and we hope you have a wonderful festive season!

All the Christmas Wishes,

Gabi from The Letters from Santa Postal Service and Many Ogilvy Hands Team

pageSummary: We are fundraising because they have provided us with so much help recently!
pageSummaryWhy: they have provided us with so much help recently!
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
On Friday 9th October, Stewart passed away peacefully at home after a short illness.

Due to the current COVID-19 restrictions, we are unable to invite all of the family and friends we would have liked to Stewarts funeral or give him the send off he deserves, and are also unable to have a collection which would go towards a charity. It is for this reason that we have chosen to fundraise online in memory of Stewart, and as a way of allowing people to pay their respects. 

We have chosen to fundraise for 3 fabulous charities that have really helped and supported us physically and emotionally during this hard time; Macmillan, Marie Curie and Strathcarron Hospice.  We all really appreciate all of your donations!

Many thanks,

Karen, Abbie and Becky x

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

On 28th September 2020 aged 90 my Dad George Russell, (BA, IEng, MSOE, MIPlantE, MBES), finally lost a three year battle with Cancer(s) that his Surgeon thought he'd have lost 1yr+ ago In fact the first cancer, (87th birthday diagnosis!) need the help of a second to win And anyone that knew him was not surprised 

An exceptional Husband, (Diamond Wedding this year), Dad, Grandad But to the end determined to still be active and always thinking of others before himself 

For example I got a job driving buses from a base with no public transport anywhere near So Dads solution  at 87 was for him to get up at 4am 6 out of 7 mornings pw and take me there And be there 12hrs later to collect

story: Our lovely mum sadly passed away last week , at her request she would like donations made to Macmillan cancer support as the nurses were incredible in her long battle with lung cancer. Anyone who knew our  mum would know how loving and caring she was and her family meant everything to her. I’m so grateful she got to meet and hold her grandchildren, she was so strong right up until the end. I hope Dad is looking after you up there mum, words can’t describe how much we’ll miss you you were my best friend and I will cherish every memory Love you forever

eventName: Virtual fun walk with MEC team
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
We are team of 124.... 124 different backgrounds, different life stories, different skills, different goals, different dreams....but we are ONE TEAM! One team with an aspiration to make a difference! During 2020 this team has been supporting business and schools to adjust to the new world, new normal..... and we still do, virtually. We are here for you. We are holding free training sessions for public on various topics, for kids, for those of you looking for a new job to upskill you. We are constantly looking for a new ways to make an impact. What a difference 2020 make to your world? We all have been forced to stop and to look at our lives through different lenses, we got to appreciate things and moments we were taking for granted... We are going  to share our virtual world together and we will make it fun! Our aim is to raise a money for those who knows a value of time on a different scale. Time... no money in the world can buy you more. If you can, please support us. Support us in making a difference! 

We are wishing you health and many happy moments! 

Enjoy every minute in a way that matters to you! 

MEC Team

story: We are a group of four postmen who are taking on the jurassic 26 mile hike to raise vital funds for Macmillan . We look forward to raising lots of money and are extremely grateful for every penny. There is a bigger , much deeper story to this which i will let my colleague Russell Story Hello and thank you for reading, myself and some good friends and my amazing cousin are going to walk 26 miles along the Jurrasic coast to raise money for Macmillan. I lost my beautiful wife Jodie to cancer in July 2018, but Macmillan did so much for us both, with care and support and financial help. They made the last year so much more bearable, giving us opportunities to spend quality time together and to give me some lasting memories. I can never thank them enough for what they have done for us. Raising money for them gives me a reason to keep going, and I'll continue to do it for as long as I can. They care for the people left behind too and have offered me counselling on several occasions. I'm lucky to have some good friends and family to support me, and it is a struggle at times. I just want to make my Jodie proud and give back to such a worthy cause. Thanks for supporting my fundraising. pageSummary: Raising Money because he couldn’t be saved but I pray that others will
pageSummaryWhy: he couldn’t be saved but I pray that others will
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Alexander (Alex) Meek
story:
So here’s my story...On the 14th April 2020 life changed forever as my beloved ‘always & forever’ Alex left this world for another. He went to bed and due to a sudden and catastrophic cardiac arrest he never woke up again. There was no opportunity for final hugs and no goodbyes.

Alex would have been celebrating his 55th birthday on the 16th October 2020, instead the week marks the 6month anniversary of his passing. He had so much life left to live, places to visit and plans for the future.

At the time of his death many people asked if there was to be a fundraiser/cause they could donate to in his memory. At the height of the Covid-19 lockdown I was aware that a lot was being asked of people financially and opted to wait. 

Ironically this year the 16th October is also “National Start a Heart Day” hosted by the British Heart Foundation and Resuscitation Council UK.  

Every year in the UK 80% of Cardiac Arrests occur in the home. Fewer than one in ten people survive an out of hospital event. This campaign promotes the importance of teaching life saving CPR skills and the provision of Heart Start Defibrillators in community settings to change this devastating statistic. 

Alex couldn’t be saved but others can! 

To mark this I have decided the time now feels right to open up this Just Giving page for anyone who wishes to donate to the British Heart Foundation and support their groundbreaking work in Alexs memory. 

My eternal thanks for all your support.

Much Love 

Emma

story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge weve faced in our 60 year history. And its led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, weve never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into groundbreaking science and support for the people who need us most. Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the worlds biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we cant drop the ball now.

story:
Sadly, every 2 hours in Hampshire somebody dies from a heart or circulatory disease, which is why we need to do all we can to continue funding our life saving research. 

The Delme Arms is collecting vital funds for the British Heart Foundation, to power pioneering research into heart and cardiovascular diseases. The money we raise will help beat heartbreak forever.

It is thanks to the support from people like you that we can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help us beat heartbreak forever.

Thanks!

story:
As a result of the latest developments, we are unable to go ahead with thousands of collections planned across the UK in the coming months. Guide Dogs remains committed to supporting people with sight loss across the UK.

It has never been more important to come together online and support one another. We appreciate times are difficult right now, but for people with sight loss, social isolation can be their every day. 

By hosting a virtual collection for Guide Dogs, every pound you or your group raises will ensure we can continue to help people with sight loss and feel less alone, now and in the future. It costs £13 a day to support each of our life changing dogs.

story:
Welcome to our online bucket collection!  We at Thames Valley Fundraising Branch are missing seeing everyone at our regular collections and trading events but due to Covid 19 we have been unable to attend any events since mid March. 

We hope to be out and about in the community with our fundraising collections and our trading stall as soon as is safe to do so, but in the meantime we hope you will be able to support us and donate to our virtual collection on this page.

We appreciate that times are really difficult at the moment, however we need support from the general public now more than ever before to make sure Guide Dogs can continue to provide our life-changing services.

story:
Citi are aiming to raise 350,000 to enable Guide Dogs to create 178 life-changing partnerships. With our support, Guide Dogs will match people with sight loss on the London waiting list to guide dogs or volunteer sighted guides.

About Our London Charity Partner Guide Dogs

Losing your sight shouldn't also mean losing your independence, confidence and freedom, but unfortunately, our world is a tough place when you cant see. In the UK, there are 360,000 people who are blind or partially sighted and half of them do not leave their homes alone.

Guide Dogs provide life-changing services:
- Guide Dogs
- Volunteer sighted guides (My Guides)
- Support for children and young people
- Orientation and mobility specialists
- Technology
- Support for friends and family

pageSummaryWhy: This charity is very close to my heart
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

Hi everyone 

I have chosen to shave all my hair off for guide dogs as its a charity very close to my heart as i have a retired guide dog called una shes a dark labradoodle and a working guide dog called victor hes a golden retriever . without this charity i wouldnt have the independence i have today my guide dogs have opened up so many doors for me and i am forever greatful for these wonderful dogs and this great charity .

I was born with a condition called oculocutaneous albinism which affects my eyes hair and skin i have no pigment so my hair is very blonde my skin is very light and my eyes let in alot of light so unfortunately i cant see much i also have nystagmus which is involuntary movement of the eyes i was registered blind when i was 2 years old i have no central vision and blurry around the edges i do well with the little vision i have    when i was younger the doctors told my mum and dad i would never be able to dye my hair or go on holiday luckily i have been on holiday and managed to dye my hair even though sometimes it stains or washes out straight away its just luck so anyone that knows me knows i love to colour my hair rainbow colours the brighter the better for me  so this is a big deal for me shaving all my hair off 

Thank you for reading

story:
Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. 

Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

pageSummary: I am walking the whole length of Hadrian’s Wall because I have lost my sister, Lesley Clarke, to cancer
pageSummaryWhat: I am walking the whole length of Hadrian’s Wall
pageSummaryWhy: I have lost my sister, Lesley Clarke, to cancer
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Lesley Clarke
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Giving is the best therapy  ! Cancer at some point in everyone’s life will visit you, whether that is a family member, a friend or yourself. It is always there in the background and is not fussy at who it will visit next. 

I lost my lovely sister, Lesley Clarke, last year to a form of cancer that was extremely aggressive and she was taken from us in days. It was completely unexpected and it is fair to say our close knit family is still recovering from this loss. I have had a few dark moments in the 18 months since she left us, but she would have wanted us all to carry on and be happy. In her honour I will be walking the full length of Hadrian’s Wall in November (84 miles in 7 days) with my son Jamie. It is the least I can do as she gave me so much in many ways. Love you always Lesley x

Please support my cause it will mean a lot to me and many others. Thank you.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Jim Prendergast
story:
At the Marie Curie Hospice, Liverpool, we give expert care to people with a terminal illness, and their loved ones every day of the year. Our hospice team includes doctors, nurses, physiotherapists, social workers and many more, and is supported by local people who freely volunteer their time and energy to help us run the hospice.

As well as being a place where people can stay to get the expert care they need in a friendly and homely setting, we also support people visiting with clinics and therapies. These include yoga, exercise classes and relaxation. People using the day unit can also get together over a freshly cooked lunch from our chefs.

Relatives and friends can visit any time of the day or night, and stay with their loved ones if they wish to. 

We need to raise £6,397 per day to run the hospice, so every penny counts. Thank you for helping to make sure more people with a terminal illness in in Liverpool, get the care and support they need.

pageSummary: We Are Raising Money because Every Ill Individual Needs Support
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
As Christmas is approaching, we are aware how difficult this year has been for most. We have witnessed people unable to say goodbye to their loved ones due to the current pandemic. That’s why this year, at MPS pharmacy we have decided to raise money for a charity called Marie Curie. Marie Curie is a charity that provides support to terminally ill individuals as well as support to the families. 

As well as a general donation page, we are also running a few raffles this year. You have a chance to win, a chocolate bouquet, a MONAT luxury hair product set, 2 bath and body works festive hand soaps and also a children’s doctors play set. If you would like to be in within a chance of winning, please pop into MPS Pharmacy (46-47 The Market, Rosehill, Surrey, SM1 3HE)

We want to take the time to thank each and every member of the local community for their understanding and patience this year. We know it hasn’t been an easy one, but we are grateful for the incredible amounts of support we have received. 

Thank you xx

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
On Friday 9th October, Stewart passed away peacefully at home after a short illness.

Due to the current COVID-19 restrictions, we are unable to invite all of the family and friends we would have liked to Stewarts funeral or give him the send off he deserves, and are also unable to have a collection which would go towards a charity. It is for this reason that we have chosen to fundraise online in memory of Stewart, and as a way of allowing people to pay their respects. 

We have chosen to fundraise for 3 fabulous charities that have really helped and supported us physically and emotionally during this hard time; Macmillan, Marie Curie and Strathcarron Hospice.  We all really appreciate all of your donations!

Many thanks,

Karen, Abbie and Becky x

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
The UK & Ireland Sea Anglers (Eastbourne Fishermen) is fundraising in aid of RNLI lifeboats that protect hundreds of communities through their 24-hour search and rescue service. 

RNLI Crews rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. From the stunning Dorset, Sussex and Kent coastlines to the unpredictable tidal Thames, our favourite places are enjoyed by millions of people from across the country every year. 

But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need our help and we will always be there to answer that call. The RNLI relies on donations from you the public to continue saving lives at sea, but we havent been able to fundraise this year and we need your help.

Thank you for your support

story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

pageSummary: We are taking part in the Big Winter Wander because we love nature and want to protect our wildlife.
pageSummaryWhat: We are taking part in the Big Winter Wander
pageSummaryWhy: we love nature and want to protect our wildlife.
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice there's less wildlife than there used to be. That's because half of all UK species are in decline - we're losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, we can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now it's our time to give back.

Stanley loves to walk and play outdoors, just as I did when I was a child. But there is less and less green space for little ones to run wild in. We want to care for and protect our trees, wildlife and environment, for Stanley and his generation and for those who come after.

By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

charity.description: Oxfam is a global movement of people who won’t live with the injustice of poverty. Together we save lives in disasters. We help people build better lives for themselves. We speak out on the big issues, like inequality and climate change. And we won’t stop until we end poverty for everyone. Join us
charity.name: Oxfam
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Oxfam is a global movement of millions of people working together to end poverty. They provide safe, clean water for all, respond to emergencies, fight climate change, tackle the coronavirus and strive for women and gender justice.


At times like these I think it is important not to forget those in need and to do what we can to help. To raise money to support people in need around the world, I am running 300km in October. 

Thank you for visiting my page and your donation x

charity.description: Médecins Sans Frontières / Doctors Without Borders (MSF) is the world's leading medical humanitarian aid organisation. We work in over 70 countries - in conflict zones, natural disasters and epidemics. We are independent, neutral and impartial. We provide medical care where it's needed most.
charity.name: Medecins Sans Frontieres / Doctors Without Borders (MSF)
pageSummary: We are a student-led society at St George's because we are very passionate about MSF's work!
pageSummaryWhat: We are a student-led society at St George's
pageSummaryWhy: we are very passionate about MSF's work!
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
We are a student-led society which functions as a helping hand for MSF. We are a team of healthcare students from St. George's, University of London who are very passionate about the work that MSF does. 

Our goal is to support them by organising campaigns, fundraising and highlighting their compassionate work. MSF's work is founded on the principles of impartiality, independence and neutrality. 

We are running a fundraising campaign over the month of November for the coronavirus appeal run by MSF. Run, walk or cycle 5k/10k and donate £5 to our page :) Then, nominate 3 people and let us raise money for our fight against COVID19. 

Let's get active!!
title: Get active for MSF!
image.caption: NA
media.images.image.caption: NA

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. 

Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good.

With clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene, children are born healthier. They get the chance to go to school and grow up to become adults. Women and men get to earn a living. Whole communities start to thrive. 

It sounds normal and it should be.
